---
description: Ban em dashes and double hyphens in user-facing strings and docs (not LLM prompt bodies or comments)
globs: "**/*.md,**/*.py"
alwaysApply: false
---

# No Em Dashes or Double Hyphens

Never use em dashes (`—`) or use double hyphens (`--`) as a substitute for an em dash in:

- **UI strings** (labels, button text, hints, tooltips, dialog messages, placeholders, status bar text, error messages)
- **Slack messages** sent to users
- **Markdown documentation** (READMEs, docs/, ROADMAP.md, etc.)
- **Log entries** written to wiki articles (e.g. `log.md`)

In **`*.py`**, treat string literals the same way when they are **user-facing** (what the user sees in the app). **Do not** apply this rule to **LLM system prompts**, **LLM instruction strings**, or **ordinary code comments**: those may use `--` or other punctuation as needed; rephrase GUI copy instead of changing prompt engineering style to satisfy typography rules.

## Replacements

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `"Got it — doing X..."` | `"Got it. Doing X..."` |
| `"field — no explanation"` | `"field. No explanation."` |
| `"X — Y"` (separator) | `"X: Y"` |
| `"(P1 — use this for P0)"` | `"(P1; use this for P0)"` |
| `"## 2026-01-01 -- Log entry"` | `"## 2026-01-01: Log entry"` |

## Why

Em dashes render inconsistently across plain-text contexts (Slack, terminal,
Word, PDF). Double hyphens are an informal substitute that looks unpolished.
Both are easy to avoid with a period, colon, or semicolon.

## Exceptions (these are fine)

- CLI flag names: `--config`, `--help`
- Section divider lines in code: `# ---`
- Code comments that use `--` for ASCII art or horizontal rules (outside user-visible UI copy)
- Markdown tables that use `---` as column separators
- **LLM system prompts and prompt-construction code** in `*.py` (see scope above)
